SIMPLE: ponder
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ponder
<hw>Pon"der</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Pondered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Pondering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>ponderare</ets>, fr. <ets>pondus</ets>, <ets>ponderis</ets>, a
weight, fr. <ets>pendere</ets> to weigh: cf. F.
<ets>pond⟦eacute⟧rer</ets>. See <er>Pendant</er>, and cf. <er>Pound</er>
a weight.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To weigh.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To weigh in the mind; to view with deliberation; to
examine carefully; to consider attentively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Ponder</qex> the path of thy feet.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. iv.
26.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To <er>Ponder</er>, <er>Consider</er>,
<er>Muse</er>.</syn> <usage> To <xex>consider</xex> means to view or
contemplate with fixed thought. To <xex>ponder</xex> is to dwell upon
with long and anxious attention, with a view to some practical result or
decision. To <xex>muse</xex> is simply to think upon continuously with
no definite object, or for the pleasure it gives. We <xex>consider</xex>
any subject which is fairly brought before us; we <xex>ponder</xex> a
concern involving great interests; we <xex>muse</xex> on the events of
childhood.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ponder</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ponder
<hw>Pon"der</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To think; to deliberate; to
muse; -- usually followed by <xex>on</xex> or <xex>over</xex>.</def>
<rj><au>Longfellow.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ponderability</ent>⟦br⟧
